"Shinohara Y., Kumagai T., Otsuki K., Kume A., Wada N.","Impact of climate change on runoff from a mid-latitude mountainous catchment in central Japan",2009,"Hydrological Processes","23","10",,"1418","1429",,,10.1002/hyp.7264,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-65449132353&partnerID=40&md5=0aa5679f32eddeb5101cc8b73a1fb8ea","Kasuya Research Forest, Kyushu University, Sasaguri, Fukuoka 811-2415, Japan; Ashoro Research Forest, Kyushu University, Ashoro-cho, Hokkaido 089-3705, Japan; Center for Far Eastern Studies, University of Toyama, Toyama 930-8555, Japan","Shinohara, Y., Kasuya Research Forest, Kyushu University, Sasaguri, Fukuoka 811-2415, Japan; Kumagai, T., Kasuya Research Forest, Kyushu University, Sasaguri, Fukuoka 811-2415, Japan; Otsuki, K., Kasuya Research Forest, Kyushu University, Sasaguri, Fukuoka 811-2415, Japan; Kume, A., Ashoro Research Forest, Kyushu University, Ashoro-cho, Hokkaido 089-3705, Japan; Wada, N., Center for Far Eastern Studies, University of Toyama, Toyama 930-8555, Japan","Hydrologic balance in high-altitude, mid-latitude mountain areas is important in terms of the water resources available to associated lowlands. This study examined how current and historical shifts in precipitation (P) patterns and concurrent increases in temperature (T) affected runoff (Q) and other hydrologic components in a mid-latitude mountain catchment of central Japan, using a combination of long-term data and a simplified hydrologic model, along with their stochastic treatment. The availability of intensive meteorological and hydrological data from the period 1997-2001 allowed the derivation of key relationships for the current climate that tie the forcing term to the parameters or state variables. By using the data recorded in the period 1965-2001, the force for driving the historical simulation was generated. Based on this model and historical shifts in P and T, the probability density functions of Q (pdf(Q)) was computed. A main novelty in this study is that such a stochastic representation, which is useful for considering the influence of projected shifts in environmental factors on the hydrologic budget, was provided. Despite the large increase in the rate of T in winter and spring, pdf(Q) in spring and summer varied appreciably during the time studied mainly because of an increase in snowmelt. An interannual change in whole-year Q was robust to shifts in T because while Q in spring increased, in summer it decreased, implying a crucial effect of global warming on mountain hydrologic regimes is change in the timing of Q. Copyright © 2009 John Wiley & Sons, Ltd.","Greenhouse warming; Snow hydrology; Snowmelt; Stochastic processes; Temperate forest; Water balance","Greenhouse warming; Snow hydrology; Snowmelt; Stochastic processes; Temperate forest; Water balance; Catchments; Climatology; Global warming; Greenhouses; Hydraulic models; Landforms; Probability density function; Probability distributions; Random processes; Runoff; Snow; Snow melting systems; Stochastic models; Water; Water resources; annual variation; climate change; glacial hydrology; global warming; hydrological modeling; midlatitude environment; mountain environment; precipitation (climatology); probability density function; runoff; snowmelt; stochasticity; temperate forest; water budget; Asia; Eurasia; Far East; Japan",,,,,,"Arnell, N.W., Reynard, N.S., The effects of climate change due to global warming on river flows in Great Britain (1996) Journal of Hydrology, 183, pp. 397-424. , DOI: 10.1016/0022-1694(95)02950-8; Bristow, K.L., Campbell, G.S., On the relationship between incoming solar radiation and daily maximum and minimum temperature (1984) Agricultural and Forest Meteorology, 31, pp. 159-166. , DOI: 10.1016/0168-1923(84)90017-0; Campbell, G.S., Norman, J.M., (1998) An Introduction to Environmental Biophysics, , 2nd edn. Springer: New York; de Bruin, H.A.R., Stricker, J.N.M., Evaporation of grass under non-restricted soil moistu